TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Death of Management — A Search for Causes
AU  - Rimler, George Warren
Y1  - 1976/04/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1976.4408691
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1976.4408691
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 126
EP  - 128
VL  - 1
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article the author provides his opinion on why he believes the study of management is dead. He believes that the field has become to concerned with what he calls trivia and is no longer concerned with what is actually taking place in the real world. He argues that there has been a communication failure and that the pressure universities place on publishing has watered down the quality of work. He closes by saying that management failed because it was not focused on the issues of the day.
AB  - In this article the author provides his opinion on why he believes the study of management is dead. He believes that the field has become to concerned with what he calls trivia and is no longer concerned with what is actually taking place in the real world. He argues that there has been a communication failure and that the pressure universities place on publishing has watered down the quality of work. He closes by saying that management failed because it was not focused on the issues of the day.
